Anonymous Thu 25 Feb 2021 12:14:02 No.36615360 Report
Quoted By:
>>36601684
>The Elements of Style
is another one I would recommend, It has the advantage of being very short as well.
>The War of Art
is another one that gets recommended often, though I personally haven't read it yet.

But I would also advise to take all the advice from all books on writing with a grain of salt. I've listened to a lot of writer interviews, mostly on the Tim Ferris podcast. Ferris is kind of efficiency nut and he loves drilling down into writer processes and habits and the take away from those interviews is that every successful writer, and it's not like hes interviewing anyone who is bad at it, has their own process.

Like the advice given is so wide and varied that the only reasonable conclusions is to do what works for you. That's even true of style unfortunately, lots of really prolific and celebrated authors are known for writing well in spite of breaking rules. Look at Cormac McCarthy's text sometime and you'll see what I'm talking about.

The only real problem with those kind of stylist deviations is that weak writers, like a lot of bad artists, hide behind the "it's just my style" excuse. You can usually tell it's an excuse when the writing is terribly inconsistent. McCarthy's books deviate from style rules, but they deviate consistently and you recognize any page of text from his books as his own. Bad writing will be all over the place, following rules one minute and abandoning them randomly in the next.
